For 12-Jun-2026 at 09:41, the reboot history you posted does not show a reboot on that date:

Jun 10 06:40 reboot
Jun 18 07:42 reboot
Jun 22 06:49 reboot

So if the server froze at 09:41 on 12-Jun-2026, then it likely experienced one of these situations:

1. Soft lockup / CPU hang (system alive but not responding)


2. Process deadlock (critical StarlingX/OpenStack services stuck)


3. Network hang (host reachable locally but not remotely)


4. Storage I/O stall (Ceph, disk, filesystem, multipath issues)


5. RT kernel scheduling issue (you're running 6.6.0-1-rt-amd64)


6. Watchdog recovered the system later without an immediate reboot



First determine whether the OS actually crashed

Check the boot history around that date:

last -x | grep "Jun 12"

If there is no reboot on Jun 12, then the kernel never restarted.

Check kernel logs around 09:41

grep "2026-06-12T09:4" /var/log/kern.log
grep "2026-06-12T09:4" /var/log/syslog

Look for:

soft lockup
hard LOCKUP
hung task
blocked for more than
rcu stall
watchdog
BUG:
kernel panic

Search for hung tasks

grep -iE "hung task|soft lockup|hard lockup|rcu" /var/log/kern.log

Check StarlingX host watchdog

Since your logs show hostwd is active:

grep "2026-06-12" /var/log/hostwd.log

Look for:

quorum loss
degrade
heartbeat failure

Check maintenance logs

grep "2026-06-12" /var/log/mtcAgent.log
grep "2026-06-12" /var/log/mtcClient.log

Most useful command

If the logs are still available:

journalctl --since "2026-06-12 09:30:00" --until "2026-06-12 10:00:00"

or

journalctl -k --since "2026-06-12 09:30:00" --until "2026-06-12 10:00:00"

